Thanks for reading this far. It's certainly very hard for me to write about the war.

Despite 10+ years of living abroad, I consider Ukraine my home. I dream of coming back, helping rebuild it even better than it was. Dream of my kids playing with their grandparents and cousins.

My wife has distant relatives in Russia. After 2014 (first invasion) the relationships cooled. On Feb 24th they claimed it was Ukraine who attacked Russia. When we showed them pictures from Bucha, they called it fake and cut all the ties. Haven't heard from them ever since.

Our relatives in the occupied Kherson region are living in fear. Younger families who could afford it fled. Anyone with the slightest link to supporting Ukraine gets a "visit" from the occupier military.

How's my family?

My parents live in central Ukraine, ignoring the frequent air raid sirens, and have no electricity for a good half of the day.

My sister fled to Germany with her daughter. Found a job, trying to make the ends meet. But it's mentally very taxing.

Russia is trying to distract the west from the crimes. It makes ridiculous claims (and keeps getting proven wrong), hints that the world won't survive without their oil and gas (it will), suggests it's all Ukraine's fault for not negotiating (it's not).

But the most important reason Ukraine is winning is that the people are determined to fight back.

For every soldier on the frontline, we have a network of volunteers who prepare food, deliver supplies, fix cars and equipment, 3D-print drone grenade launchers.

Ukraine's army has made a lot of progress since the beginning of the invasion. A lot of this is thanks to the weapons donated and sold by the US, Germany, Turkey, Poland, and others.

The support from the west, especially in heavy artillery and air defense systems, is crucial. https://t.co/AqARseb6KX
